        "title_zh": "英国人为何如今更信任天气预报员",
        "url": "https://www.economist.com/node/2026-07-11/43",
        "summary_md": "### 🌟 一句话核心主旨\n得益于技术进步、极端天气预警机制的完善,以及1987年大风暴记忆的淡去,英国民众对天气预报员的信任度显著上升,但英国建筑与制冷基础设施的短板仍未跟上气候变化带来的现实挑战。\n\n### 🔍 核心观点与论据拆解\n1. **历史阴影与信任低谷**:1987年大风暴(Deadly cyclone)是英国人对天气预报员长期不信任的根源。BBC名嘴气象员Michael Fish曾公开表示观众不必担心飓风来袭,然而数小时后风暴席卷英国。YouGov 2017年民调显示,当时仅过半数民众信任天气预报员。\n2. **信任度的显著逆转**:最新YouGov民调显示,现已有62%的英国人信任天气预报员,持怀疑态度者降至25%。虽仍远低于护士(86%),但远超经济学家(37%)和政客(仅4%)。\n3. **技术与精度飞跃**:1987年风暴倒逼英国投资天气预报技术。Channel 4气象主持人Liam Dutton介绍,其依赖的模型已将英国划分为边长2公里的网格,十年前最高分辨率仅为12公里。如今提前四天的预报精度已可媲美1990年代提前一天的预报。Met Office的Alex Deakin将此归因于技术进步,且25岁以下年轻人因成长于预报可靠的时代,信任度最高。\n4. **极端天气与沟通升级**:气候变化使热浪、强降水等极端事件更频繁、更具危险性,精准预警反而强化了信任。Met Office自2015年起效仿美国(1950年代做法)为大型风暴命名,最近一次为今年4月的「Storm Dave」;同时启用颜色分级高温预警,今年6月发布的红色警报是英国第二次,首次为2022年。\n5. **应对能力的结构性短板**:老式住宅设计本就保温蓄热,加之法规限制,新建住宅大多未装空调。政府虽已开放补贴,允许安装兼具制冷功能的空气源热泵(此前被排除在主流补贴之外),但当气温突破30°C时,大多数英国人仍难逃酷暑困扰。\n\n### 🤨 争议与潜在挑战\n原文未涉及明显争议,仅指出气候变化在让极端天气预报更受重视的同时,也使预报本身变得更困难(Met Office Alex Deakin观点)。\n\n### 🔮 未来趋势预判\n基于文章事实可推断:面对气候变化导致的极端天气增多,英国对精细化预报和预警沟通的需求将持续上升,但住宅制冷基础设施的滞后可能成为公共健康风险点,迫使政府在建筑法规或补贴政策上进一步调整。",
        "content_raw": "<p><span class=\"te_section_title\">Britain</span><span class=\"te_fly_span\"> | A hot topic</span></p>\n<h1>Why Britons now trust weather forecasters</h1>\n<h3>Credit greater accuracy and better communication</h3>\n<h3>July 9th 2026</h3>\n<p>Chatting about the weather is a national pastime in Britain—and successive heatwaves have recently given Britons lots to discuss. In the past, the obsession did not translate into faith in weather forecasters. Memories lingered of the “great storm” of 1987, a deadly cyclone. The BBC’s best-known forecaster, Michael Fish (pictured), said on air that a woman had called in worrying there might be a “hurricane” approaching Britain. “If you’re watching, don’t worry, there isn’t!” he quipped. Hours later the storm struck.</p>\n<p>YouGov, a pollster, found in 2017 that barely half of people trusted forecasters to give them accurate information about the weather. But that has changed. A recent YouGov survey finds that now 62% of Britons trust them and just 25% are sceptical—still far behind trust in nurses (86%), but well ahead of economists (37%), let alone politicians (a mere 4%). The change is partly because forecasts are more accurate than ever thanks to advances in technology, suggests Alex Deakin of the Met Office. It also helps that fewer people today remember the 1987 storm.</p>\n<p>Indeed, that storm prompted investment in weather-forecasting tech and communications protocols. Liam Dutton, a weather presenter for Channel 4 News, says the model he relies on divides Britain into squares of 2km (1.2 miles) a side, whereas a decade ago the highest resolution possible was 12km. The average accuracy of a forecast four days into the future is comparable to that of a one-day forecast in the 1990s. Under-25s, who grew up in an era of reliable forecasts, are by a large margin most likely to trust forecasters.</p>\n<p>Climate change has raised the stakes by causing more extreme, sometimes life-threatening shocks such as prolonged heatwaves and sudden heavy downpours. “Being more accurate when it comes to those extreme events builds trust,” says Mr Deakin (though climate change also makes forecasting trickier). Since 2015, following the practice in America since the 1950s, the Met Office has given names to the biggest storms. The most recent was Storm Dave, in April. The agency believes this has helped engage the public. There are also colour-coded warnings for heat. A <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/science-and-technology/2026/06/24/global-warming-has-made-europes-heatwave-2-4c-worse\">red alert in June</a> was Britain’s second, after one in 2022.</p>\n<p>Though it is now easier to predict the British weather, dealing with it remains a challenge. Older houses are built to hoard heat in the chilly winter; regulations mean that even most new-build homes lack air conditioning. The government has at least started to offer grants for homeowners to install heat pumps that also have a cooling function, which had previously been excluded from the most popular subsidy scheme. Nonetheless, when the mercury passes 30°C most Britons will continue to lose their cool. <span class=\"span_ufinish\">■</span></p>\n<p>For more expert analysis of the biggest stories in Britain, <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/newsletters/blighty\">sign up</a> to Blighty, our weekly subscriber-only newsletter.</p>\n<p>This article was downloaded by <a class=\"producer_link\" href=\"https://z-lib.io\">zlibrary</a> from <a class=\"origin_link\" href=\"https://www.economist.com//britain/2026/07/05/why-britons-now-trust-weather-forecasters\">https://www.economist.com//britain/2026/07/05/why-britons-now-trust-weather-forecasters</a> </p>",
