            "para_id": "art_2026-07-11_062_p5",
            "en_html": "<p>“The stock MARKET is not the economy” might be a cliché, but it is still jarring to see quite how far the two can part ways. Surely economic growth should be good for shareholders? Yet study after study has suggested the opposite. One by Jay Ritter of the University of Florida, for instance, compared the returns on 16 countries’ stock markets with their GDP growth per person between 1900 and 2002. The two appeared, if anything, to be negatively correlated—meaning that the faster a country became richer, the worse its investors tended to do.</p>",
            "zh_text": "「股市不是经济」虽是老生常谈,但看到两者竟能背道而驰到如此地步,仍令人错愕。经济增长理应对股东有利吧?然而一项又一项研究表明事实恰恰相反。例如,佛罗里达大学的杰伊·里特对16个国家1900年至2002年间股市回报与人均GDP增速进行了比较,结果发现两者似乎呈负相关——也就是说,一个国家富裕得越快,其投资者往往表现越差。"
